metadata.name: Unsolicited abstraction of modern times #3
metadata.description:
This piece is an abstraction and a reflection on the last era, on all that we have built and become. Are we proud of it or has it just been the result of iterating through the days? Since the technology boom, we have experienced great improvements, but perhaps also massive ...mistakes?  

Inspired by textbooks of the 80s, with elements that remind us of industry, technology, networks and systems, "Unsolicited abstraction of modern times" invites us to question our work to date. Has everything really changed?

unknowable 2022




Usage:
press [s] - save pixels (png)
press [p] - save vectors (svg)

metadata.name: Action Fields #403
metadata.description:
A generative painting based on abstract expressionism and the action paintings of Jackson Pollock.

Several different flow fields are used to create paths which are then painted in one of four different styles (pastel, paint, Pollock, black+gold). Additional features affect the background, path length + angles, level of detail, and mess (drips and splats). 

NOTES: 
- Some variations of the Pollock style may appear slightly different between browsers, but will render consistently in the same browser. 
- On slower devices, it may take some time to being drawing due to the background rendering.
- If you get a browser warning that the page is taking a long time, press continue.

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.
Press ’s’ to save a screenshot. Image size is 1200x928px
Press ’p’ to pause/resume.

Add '&size=#' to the end of the live view URL to render a variation of your edition at a resolution from 300 to 5,000 px. The ideal higher resolution is 2,000px.

metadata.name: Memo #161
metadata.description:
Memo is a abstract expression of memories written on small pieces of paper, pictures of important moments or a reminder of all the things You have forgotten.

Memo is created with P5JS. Large number of rectangles are packed in loops to the canvas with a random rectangle packing algorithm with simple collision detection. 
The looped area varies from 1 vertical or horizontal rectangle to 8x8 grid. Packed area is created with simple random walking grid loop.
60+ color palettes are handpicked and they can appear reversed. 
One random palette is picked for each piece and p5js.noise() drives the colors, size and angle on the rects with lots of attributes.

Click 'n' to add white noise.
Click 's' to save image as jpeg.

Click '1' to 1x pixelDensity(3600 x 6400 or 6400 x 3600 px - default).
Click '2' to 2x pixelDensity(7200 x 12800 or 12800 x 7200 px).

VGA 2022 / CC BY-NC 4.0

metadata.name: 0xSiebe #32
metadata.description: 0xSiebe is a series exploring gradients, layers and grids. It builds on my ever evolving grid framework and it is my first collection that makes use of shaders. Inspiration I got from artists like Martin Grasser and from my general fascination of light and soft colors.

metadata.name: borders #359
Alien Signs #82
metadata.description: Famous in the galaxy curves are featured here. The ones that require only trigonometrical functions, thus accessible to all humanoids. Projections of pure math. Archimedean spiral, lemniscate, circle and occasional fish could be found. Black and white palette is rare. Occasional highway is crossing all the symbols. Press "e" to save image.

metadata.name: Copenhagen Interpretation #56
metadata.description:
The Copenhagen Interpretation of quantum physics suggests that objects don't have physical properties until being observed.

In this generative piece by itsgalo and Spøgelsesmaskinen, a set of objects are being held in "superposition" and finally positioned when observed and minted.

Use mouse/touch to zoom, pan, and rotate. Press 's' to grab a screenshot. Best viewed in Firefox.

metadata.name: Moiré #5
metadata.description:
Moiré pattern is a geometrical design created by superposing set of lines to another set. The pattern can be found in our daily lives such as LCD monitor screens and screen windows. 

studio2009 created the pattern by overlapping two sets of polygons created with multiple lines. To add some variations, we have added color ways, rotation, and distortion which can be found in features. The distortion in particular are available in three different modes: simple, exponential, and tangential. Please enjoy.
